      "using that `7` is the inverse of `5 mod 17`:\n\nWe can write:\n`n ≡ 7 * (5 * n) mod 17` because `7 * 5 ≡ 1 mod 17`.  \nThus `n ≡ 7 * 8 ≡ 56 ≡ 5 mod 17`.  \n\nBut in Lean, we can't directly reason with congruences, so instead we can compute `(7 * (5 * n)) % 17 = (7 * 8) % 17 = 56 % 17 = 5`.  \nBut `(7 * (5 * n)) % 17 = (35 * n) % 17 = (1 * n) % 17 = n % 17`, since `35 ≡ 1 mod 17`.  \nThus, `n % 17 = 5`.\n\nTo formalize this, note that `(7 * (5 * n)) % 17 = (35 * n) % 17 = (1 * n) % 17 = n % 17`.  \nBut also `(7 * (5 * n)) % 17 = (7 * ((5 * n) % 17)) % 17 = (7 * 8) % 17 = 56 % 17 = 5`.  \nThus `n % 17 = 5`.\n\nBut this is essentially:\n`n % 17 = (35 * n) % 17 = (7 * (5 * n)) % 17 = (7 * 8) % 17 = 5`.\n\n### Step 4: Implement in Lean\n\nFirst compute `(7 * (5 * n)) % 17` in two ways:\n1. `(7 * (5 * n)) % 17 = (35 * n) % 17 = n % 17`, because `35 ≡ 1 mod 17`.\n2. `(7 * (5 * n)) % 17 = (7 * ((5 * n) % 17)) % 17 = (7 * 8) % 17 = 5`.\n\nThus, `n % 17 = 5`.\n\nBut in Lean, to avoid reasoning with congruences, we can instead use that for any `n`, we have:\n`(35 * n) % 17 = n % 17` because `35 % 17 = 1`. \n\nIndeed:\n`(35 * n) % 17 = ((35 % 17) * (n % 17)) % 17 = (1 * (n % 17)) % 17 = n % 17`.\n\nBut also, `35 * n = 7 * (5 * n)`, so:\n`(35 * n) % 17 = (7 * (5 * n)) % 17 = (7 * ((5 * n) % 17)) % 17 = (7 * 8) % 17 = 56 % 17 = 5`.\n\nThus, `n % 17 = 5`.\n\nBut Lean can compute `56 % 17` as `5`, because `17 * 3 = 51`, `56 - 51 = 5`.\n\n### Step 5: Implementation Details in Lean\n\nWe will do the following steps in Lean:\n\n1. Compute `(35 * n) % 17 = n % 17`:\n   - Because `35 % 17 = 1`, `(35 * n) % 17 = ((35 % 17) * (n % 17)) % 17 = (1 * (n % 17)) % 17 = n % 17`.\n\n2. Compute `(35 * n) % 17 = 5`:\n   - `35 * n = 7 * (5 * n)`, so `(35 * n) % 17 = (7 * (5 * n)) % 17`.\n   - `(7 * (5 * n)) % 17 = (7 * ((5 * n) % 17)) % 17` (by properties of `%`).\n   - `(5 * n) % 17 = 8` (given).\n   - So, `(7 * (5 * n)) % 17 = (7 * 8) % 17 = 56 % 17`.\n   - `56 % 17 = 5`.\n\nTherefore, `n % 17 = 5`.\n\nAlternatively, in Lean, to avoid using the `35 * n` step, we can instead note that:\n`n % 17` can only take values `0..16`, and for each of them, we can check that if `5 * n ≡ 8 mod 17`, then `n ≡ 5 mod 17`.\n\nBut the first method is more general and doesn't require checking 17 cases. \n\n### Step 6: Formal Lean Proof\n\nHere is the formal Lean proof:\n\n1. We have `(35 * n) % 17 = n % 17` because `35 ≡ 1 mod 17`.\n   - `35 % 17 = 1`, so `(35 * n) % 17 = (1 * (n % 17)) % 17 = n % 17`.\n2. But also `(35 * n) % 17 = (7 * (5 * n)) % 17 = (7 * 8) % 17 = 5`.\n3. Thus, `n % 17 = 5`.\n\nBut actually in Lean, we can directly compute `(7 * (5 * n)) % 17` as `5`, because:\n`(7 * (5 * n)) % 17 = (7 * ((5 * n) % 17)) % 17 = (7 * 8) % 17 = 56 % 17 = 5`.\n\nBut also `(7 * (5 * n)) % 17 = (35 * n) % 17 = n % 17`, because `35 ≡ 1 mod 17`.\n\nSo in Lean:\n\n1. First, compute `(7 * (5 * n)) % 17` in terms of `(5 * n) % 17`:\n   - `(7 * (5 * n)) % 17 = (7 * ((5 * n) % 17)) % 17`.\n2. Substitute `(5 * n) % 17 = 8` to get `(7 * 8) % 17 = 56 % 17 = 5`.\n3. Also, `(7 * (5 * n)) % 17 = (35 * n) % 17 = ((35 % 17) * (n % 17)) % 17 = (1 * (n % 17)) % 17 = n % 17`.\n4. Thus `n % 17 = 5`.\n\nBut perhaps it is easier to use:\n`(35 * n) % 17 = n % 17`, and also `(35 * n) % 17 = (7 * (5 * n)) % 17 = 5`.\n\n### Abstract Plan\n\n1. Show that `(35 * n) % 17 = n % 17`:\n   - Because `35 ≡ 1 mod 17`.\n2. Show that `(35 * n) % 17 = 5`:\n   - Because `35 * n = 7 * (5 * n)` and `(5 * n) % 17 = 8`.\n   - So `(35 * n) % 17 = (7 * 8) % 17 = 5`.\n3. Conclude `n % 17 = 5`.\n\nBut in Lean, perhaps it is easier to just compute `(7 * (5 * n)) % 17` in two ways:\n1. `(7 * (5 * n)) % 17 = (7 * ((5 * n) % 17)) % 17 = (7 * 8) % 17 = 5`.\n2. `(7 * (5 * n)) % 17 = (35 * n) % 17 = n % 17`.\n\n### Lean Proof\n\nNow, let's translate this into Lean:\n\nFirst, note that in Lean:\n- `(a * b) % m = ((a % m) * (b % m)) % m`\n- `(a * b) % m = (a * (b % m)) % m`\n- `(a * b) % m = ((a % m) * b) % m`\n\nWe will use:\n`(7 * (5 * n)) % 17 = (7 * ((5 * n) % 17)) % 17`, which is true because `(a * b) % m = (a * (b % m)) % m`.\n\nBut also `7 * (5 * n) = 35 * n`, so `(7 * (5 * n)) % 17 = (35 * n) % 17 = ((35 % 17) * (n % 17)) % 17 = (1 * (n % 17)) % 17 = n % 17`.\n\nAlternatively, we could first calculate that `(35 * n) % 17 = n % 17`, but perhaps it is better to just work with `(7 * (5 * n)) % 17`.\n\nLet's proceed with:\n1. `(7 * (5 * n)) % 17 = (7 * 8) % 17 = 5`.\n2. `(7 * (5 * n)) % 17 = (35 * n) % 17 = n % 17`.\n\nBut to get `(35 * n) % 17 = n % 17`, note that:\n`(35 * n) % 17 = ((35 % 17) * (n % 17)) % 17 = (1 * (n % 17)) % 17 = n % 17`.\n\nBut perhaps it is better to avoid using `(a * b) % m = ((a % m) * (b % m)) % m` because Lean may not have this as a direct lemma. But it actually does: `Nat.mul_mod`.\n\n### Step-by-Step Abstract Plan\n\n1. We know `5 * n ≡ 8 mod 17`, i.e., `(5 * n) % 17 = 8`.\n2. Multiply both sides by `7`: `(7 * (5 * n)) % 17 = (7 * 8) % 17`.\n   - `(7 * 8) % 17 = 56 % 17 = 5`.\n3. But `7 * (5 * n) = 35 * n`, so `(35 * n) % 17 = 5`.\n4. However, `35 ≡ 1 mod 17`, so `(35 * n) % 17 = n % 17`.\n   - Therefore, `n %",
